To do this, we analyzed all known coronavirus genomes (3,051) to identify possible crRNAs that can target each of those genomes, ending up with approximately 6.48 million possible crRNAs (Figures 5
A and S5
). We refined this list to identify the smallest number of crRNAs that could target all known coronavirus genomes with zero mismatches. We found that just two crRNAs could target ∼50% of coronavirus genomes, including those causing COVID-19, SARS, and MERS; six crRNAs were able to target ∼91% of coronavirus genomes; and 22 crRNAs covered all sequenced coronaviruses with no mismatches (Figure 5B; Table S4). The ability to use a relatively small number of crRNAs to broadly target most or all coronavirus strains further highlights the unique power of our method in contrast to traditional pharmaceutical or vaccination approaches.
